Aqua-Coloured Toyota Aquas!

What was my inspiration?

Every time I go out in my blue Toyota Aqua, I find myself encountering so many others with the exact same car and colour! I decided to log data about the number of Toyota Aquas I saw when I went out in my car, recording things such as the time and duration of my trip, alongside what colours I saw.

Below is a photo of my car and one of its many clones.

Rate of Aquas and Time of Day

My first question was - I’m seeing so many Toyota Aquas, but I’m wondering if this changes depending on the time of day I go out? I converted my timestamps from Google Form submission from a character vector to a time format in R, and made the y-axis by dividing the number of Aquas I saw by the number of minutes I was out. I then decided to track the two numeric variables with a dot plot with a line graph, with each dot being a trip in my car.

Although the sample size was small, there are clear dips in Aqua rate before sudden peaks, which seen to occur at 3:30pm at 9:00pm. It is hard to make any inference from the limited sample, but this is an interesting visualization!

Proportion of Blue Aquas

I then wanted to see the proportion of trips where just blue Aquas were spotted, and to visualise if this proportion changes with the number of cars seen on that trip. The observations were split into equal sized groups, 1-6 cars, 7-10 and 10+ cars. I decided to make this a stacked boxplot, as is common for visualizing the proportions across different groups.

As expected, the chance of seeing a Toyota Aqua increased between the 1-6 car and 7-10 cars. Interestingly, the 10+ group has a slightly smaller proportion than the 7-10 group. This is likely due to error, which is unsurprising given the small sample size.

Trip Duration and Blue Aquas

I was very surprised that the proportion of trips with over 10 Aquas spotted only had a proportion of less than 70% of blue Aquas being seen, despite me noticing so many blue Aquas while driving! I decided to make a boxplot to see if mean length of trips where a blue Aqua was spotted were longer than those where none were seen. I felt like I was seeing many Aquas even on short trips, so this is a way of checking if I was biased!

Although there were indeed trips as short as 6 minutes where a blue aqua was spotted, the median trip time was indeed shorter when no blue Aquas were seen. Perhaps my thinking that I saw a blue Aqua everytime I stepped outside was an exaggeration!
